<DOC><DOCNO> AP900825-0004 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-08-25-90 0301EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i PM-BRF--GorbachevInsult     08-25 0132</FIRST><SECOND>PM-BRF--Gorbachev Insult,0135</SECOND><HEAD>First Soviet Arrested For Insulting President</HEAD><DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   An unemployed man who displayed a defaced portraitof Mikhail S. Gorbachev has become the first person arrested oncharges of insulting the Soviet president, a newspaper reported.   Gennady Smirnov strolled through Moscow on July 29 carrying theportrait, the newspaper Vechernaya Moskva reported Friday.According to law enforcement officials, Smirnov had pennedinsulting and slanderous words and drawings on it.   The 40-year-old man could face a $4,800 fine or a two-yearprison camp term.   Smirnov is undergoing a medical examination to determine hismental condition, Vechernaya Moskva reported.   The Soviet legislature passed the law on slandering thepresident in May after a May Day demonstration in which protestersshouted insults at Gorbachev and other leaders in Red Square.</TEXT></DOC>